recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalization. High flight call at 0:00, 0:10, and 0:28. This bird flushed from the tall grass on my approach and perched in a 1.5m tall locust sapling where it called several times before flying away. Distance from microphone ~5m.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff *4 kHz*, order 3

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Bethlehem, Upshur, Texas
recordings.rmk:
There were 6-8 Fox Sparrows in the small hollow near the road. I played an eastern Fox Sparrow Song and Smack calls using the Sibley app on my iPhone to see if I could get them to vocalize. I heard two give songs, although the recording is of only one singing. Also heard are others making the Smack call.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalization. Singing from within dense ground cover, mostly grasses and partridgepea one to two meters in height. There seems to have been an influx of Fox Sparrows with a weather front that brought ~5" of rain two days ago, with several FOSP singing in close proximity on this morning. Distance from microphone ~5m.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 700 hz, order 3

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Charles L. Armentrout Dr + Rhode Island Ave (near  Cottage City), Prince George's County, Maryland
recordings.rmk: You'll have to turn the volume way up to hear it over the highway noise, but then the song is pretty clear. Recorded during mid evening twilight in overgrown brush between pond and mowed parkland, near river and highway. Not far from tidal Anacostia River. Clear, low four-note phrase, then a pause, then a three-note B phrase. Song occurs twice in recording and each time the pause between the two phrases is a different length! Lots of White-Throated Sparrows and Song Sparrows in this brush, but this song is so low and clear, it's more like a female Baltimore Oriole, a species which is unusual but possible during winter here. Or maybe a Fox Sparrow? Recording is unmodified.
